column46: Trends and Insights Subscription Services RFQ
column47: Future Opportunity Notice: Trends and Insights Subscription Services
column48:
HS2 Ltd is developing its products, services, brand and people and wishes to understand how experiences are developing within a global context. This includes, mega, macro and micro trends related to accessibility, food/drink consumption and use of amenities within communities, catering, including seating and the digital offering on the train and at stations. As such, HS2 Ltd wishes to subscribe to an annual service that can be utilised to deliver (for an initial 12 month period) insights into trends and the future. Where specific trends are identified, where relevant to programme delivery, HS2 would then like to further explore these areas through research work packages included within the overall annual subscription. HS2 requires a supplier to provide conclusive trends and insight information that can be used to help define ongoing research areas as well as its product, services, brand and people. This support must be provided for a 12 month period and should include access to an online subscription service that HS2 can access at its convenience.  This subscription service should include support in the form of an account manager (or equivalent), who can help guide and support HS2 in its interrogation of the provided online resource.

Timescales:
- Issue RFQ Documentation: week commencing 30/01/2017;
- Deadline for Supplier RFQ Responses: week commencing 13/02/2017;
- Contract Award: week commencing 20/02/2017

Procurement Process and Next Steps:

The procurement exercise will be carried out on HS2 Ltd's e-Sourcing Portal; Bravo. All messages should be sent through the Bravo secure messaging facility once the RFQ has been published.

In order to participate in this procurement exercise, Suppliers will need to initially register on Bravo (please see the instructions for registration attached to this notice).

column47: Extension of Wysall Lane Burial Ground, Keyworth, Nottingham
column48:
Keyworth Parish Council is currently pricing the change of use of the field, located to the south west of Keyworth, within the green belt, to a burial ground extension.
The field is currently a wildflower meadow and is accessed from the existing car park that serves the cemetery adjacent to Wysall Lane.
The project comprises:
Groundworks
Excavation of ground to accommodate new pathways and car park. Excavated earth to be used to grade ground and level out ridge and furrow. Surplus earth spread over rest of wildflower meadow.
Laying new car park and footpath as drawings.
Removal of boundary hedge as drawings.
Raising manhole as drawings.
Fencing
Dismantle existing compound and reconstruct in new position as drawings.
New gate to wildflower meadow.
New post and rail fence to form new boundary as drawings.
New stile within post and rail fence. For further details, please contact Clive Hewitt.

column47: GB-Shrewsbury: DMCH 013 Bikeability Cycle Training 2017 - 2020
column48:
Shropshire Council are seeking to appoint a suitable contractor to provide Bikeability cycle training, from 1 April 2017 to 31 March 2020 following the allocation of Bikeability funding by the Department for Transport (DfT) for this period. The focus of the service will be the delivery of Bikeability Level 1/2 in primary schools and Level 3 in secondary schools during term time but provision can also be made for the delivery of Bikeability training during school holidays if the contractor is able to promote / facilitate this. Provision will also include the delivery of Bikeability Level 1, four Bikeabiltiy Plus modules and bespoke training.
      The Bikeability training service is being commissioned with the following objectives to:
      improve cycle skills and road sense
      increase confidence to cycle
      create a positive perception of cycling
      encourage, enable and facilitate more people to cycle, more safely and more often 
      increase cycling trips
      increase the number of children and adults receiving cycle training
      Staff delivering training should be fully accredited Bikeability trainers offering the DfT's Bikeability programme and the contractors training scheme must be Bikeability Registered. Full details of Bikeability are available here: http://bikeability.org.uk/

Additional information: The contracting authority considers that this contract may be suitable for economic operators that are small or medium enterprises (SMEs). However, any selection of tenderers will be based solely on the criteria set out for the procurement.

column47: Environment Agency - Supply of a jetter jet wash unit
column48:
Contract for the supply of 1x road tow jetter jet wash unit. Unit is to be towed by a vehicle with a towing capacity of 3500kg and no more. The unit is to have a minimum capacity of 100 gallons. The unit is to have a lance with 100m hose for jet washing purposes, and 100m of hose for drain jetting purposes. The drain jetting unit must be able to jet up to 300mm culverts. The unit is to be diesel powered with a bunded fuel tank. the unit is to operate with a minimum pressure of 3000 psi. The trailer is to be fitted with ball hitch towing connection, wheel nut indicators, and its own lighting system for towing. The unit must be CE marked and to current PUWER regulations.

Additional information: If tendering you will need to provide a full specification ensuring the unit matches the requirement. A certificate stating its CE authenticity. A full quotation with detailed breakdown of the required component costs to be itemised. Also to be supplied is certification for meeting PUWER requirements. To express interest, please email seb.bishop@environment-agency.gov.uk.

column47: AQP Standalone Contraceptive Vasectomy service
column48:
Commissioners within NHS Coastal West Sussex CCG wish to commission an AQP Standalone Contraceptive Vasectomy Service. This Service will deliver a safe, high quality service for NHS Coastal West Sussex CCG that offers patients a choice of provider, together with choice of location, date and time of appointments, excellent outcomes and an improved patient experience. 

In 2014-15, the overall activity for the contract comprised 137 consultations and 129 vasectomy procedures. It should be noted that under the Any Qualified Provider model, there will be no guarantees of volume or payment in the contracts awarded. The qualification window opens on 7th October 2016.

The Commissioners will be holding a Provider Information Event for all interested parties on Monday 17th October 2016. To reserve up to three places per organisation, please email claire.ferguson5@nhs.net or call 01903 708617 with contact details of those who will be attending.

The provision of a standalone contraceptive vasectomy service is a contract for a period of 3 years commencing on the 1st April 2017 with option to extend for a maximum of a further two years. 

The offer documentation comprises of the following:
Document 1 AQP Qualification Information
Document 2 AQP Application form
Document 3 Service Specification

In securing services from Providers, the authority needs assurance of competence, quality and safety standards, just as it would for services secured under a formal tender process.
Any provider will be eligible to join a list of qualified providers subject to demonstrating competency against the authoritys specified criteria. 
Please read the qualification questionnaire and the supporting offer documents very carefully since failure to comply with the requirements contained therein (including paying particular attention to Maximum Word Limits for answers) will invalidate your submission.

If qualified, your organisation will be required to accept the terms and conditions and be compliant with the NHS Standard Contract and any subsequent revisions thereof.
It should be clearly noted that certain parts of the contract e.g. Local Quality Requirements are subject to change this and every year in line with DH/Monitor Guidance. At its absolute discretion, the contracting authority will reflect these changes as it deems appropriate in this contract.
Please note that the Contracting Authority will not enter into an arrangement with any individual or organisation that does not fully accept this requirement. Please note that caveat responses will be considered as non-acceptance of this requirement.

The Contracting Authority reserves the right to change dates and times or modify any stage of the process including the introduction of additional steps or stages in order to gain additional assurance and/or maximise efficiencies.

Additional information: An electronic procurement process is being used for this procurement.
Interested parties wishing to participate must follow the process detailed below to register their details on the IN-tend  eTender system website https://in-tendhost.co.uk/soepscommissioning to gain access to further information and obtain the tender documents to be completed and returned for consideration. Any correspondence received via other means will not be responded to.
The window for questions from Applicants will close at 12pm, Tuesday 25th October 2016, allowing time for answers to be posted and applicants to complete and submit their applications by 12pm, Friday 4th November 2016. 
If Applicants are asked Clarification Questions during the Evaluation Stages, they have 48 hours in which to respond. Please ensure that you have staff available to answer the questions, which will be sent to you by email. Failure to respond in the given time could adversely impact your application.

Suppliers Instructions of how to express interest and participate in this
Tender:
1. Register your company on the e-tendering portal (this is only required
once):
 Browse to the e-tendering Portal: https://in-tendhost.co.uk/soepscommissioning  and click the link to register.
 Read and accept the terms and conditions and lick Continue.
 Enter your correct business and user details.
 Note the username you chose and click Save when complete.
 You will shortly receive an email with your unique password (please keep
this secure).
2. Express an Interest in the tender:
 Login to the portal with the username/password.
 Click the Tenders link and then select Current. (These are Pre-Qualification Questionnaires or Invitations to Tender open to any registered supplier.)
 Click on the relevant PQQ/ ITT to access the content.
 Click the Express Interest' button at the bottom of the page.
 This will move the PQQ /ITT into your My Tenders page. (This is a secure area reserved for your projects only.)
 You can now access any attachments via the relevant tabs.
 You can now use the Clarifications function to communicate with the buyerand seek any clarification.
 Note the deadline for completion, then follow the onscreen instructions to complete the PQQ/ ITT.
 There may be a mixture of online and offline actions for you to perform (there is detailed online help available).You must then submit your reply using the Publish Response button at the top of the page. If you require any further assistance please consult the online help, or contact the eTendering help desk.

To express your interest in this opportunity email ExpressionOfInterest@crowncommercial.gov.uk. To register on our e-sourcing portal click on https://gpsesourcing.cabinetoffice.gov.uk and follow the link "Register for CCS eSourcing" 

British Antarctic Survey (BAS) is currently developing a bulk fuel storage facility at its research station in Halley, Antarctica. The bulk tank storage facility is expected to be built and fully functional during the 2017 Austral season.

The facility will include up to 30 bulk fuel tanks with each tank being hosted on a dedicated cargo sledge capable of holding and temporarily moving the tanks in Antarctic conditions. There is also a requirement for a smaller number additional cargo sledges to be used as part of the logistical operations to get the fuel tanks into situ at the station.  In total a quantity of 38 sledges are required for this initiative. 

Over and above this quantity BAS also wishes to put in place a 5-year contract for the supply of the same or very similar cargo sledges to meet further operation needs that are anticipated over that period. These requirements to be available under a call-off arrangement subject to a future confirmation of needs. Subject to future funding approvals it is estimated that between 50 to 70 sledges may be required over the contract period.

Due to the complexity of operations and the environmental challenges the sledges are required to highly reliable and safe to operate in Antarctic conditions, hence should be designed for extreme cold weather and manufactured to a very high standard.

The first consignment of 38 Cargo sledges will be shipped to Antarctica via one of the BAS operated polar research ships from October 2017. Consequently delivery of the cargo sledges is required by October 2017 latest to a UK dockside (Immingham, UK) to be provided free alongside in a bonded store.  
Batch shipments of cargo sledges to the docks is acceptable provided that in total 38 cargo sledges are delivered by October 2017.

Additional information: DO NOT APPLY DIRECTLY TO THE BUYER

The registered user will receive a notification email to alert them once this has been done. column47: NETWORKS (GLOBAL WAN)
column48:
The International Campus Network (ICN) is the University's communications backbone connecting the international campuses. The University of Nottingham are seeking a Managed Service Provider (MSP) partner that has the ability to support, enable and mentor the University's service delivery capabilities. 
      
      The objective of this contract is to transform the WAN service from the static provision of bandwidth between campuses to a service that evolves from its current state to a 'state of the art' SD (Software Defined) WAN with NFV (Network Function Virtualisation).
      In collaboration with the incumbent service provider the University has developed a Global WAN Strategy. The strategy suggests a 3 Stage approach: 
      
      1. Stage 1 - Foundation 
      2. Stage 2 - Hybrid WAN
      3. Stage 3 - SD WAN and NFV 
      
      The pace at which the University evolves through these stages will be determined by its ability to execute a series of discrete tasks and work packages that prepare it for each stage and by the ability of the Managed Service Provider to evolve the services in lock step with the University.

column47: AQP Audiology Services for South Warwickshire CCG
column48:
AQP for Audiology Adult Hearing Service for Age-Related Hearing Loss (non-complex) for NHS South Warwickshire Clinical Commissioning Group (SWCCG).

NHS Arden & GEM CSU is conducting this procurement exercise on behalf of NHS South Warwickshire Clinical Commissioning Group (SWCCG) to seek suitably qualified and experienced providers to deliver the Any Qualified Provider (AQP) for Adult Hearing Service for Age-Related Hearing Loss (non-complex).

The Adult Hearing AQP Service is aimed at adults aged 55 years old and over experiencing difficulties with their hearing and communication where a GP considers they may benefit from hearing assessment and care, including the option of trying hearing aids to reduce these difficulties. 

The aim is to provide a comprehensive community-based, patient-centred, adult hearing service for age-related hearing loss in line with national guidance and local requirements.

The purpose of the AQP for Adult Hearing Service is to ensure:

	Equitable access to high and consistent quality care for all patients using the service
	A safe hearing service for patients that conforms to a recognised quality assurance tool e.g. the Improving Quality in Physiological Diagnostic Services Self-Assessment and Improvement Tool (IQIPS-SAIT). The service must also recognise published clinical guidelines/good practice.

It is the intention of the Commissioners to enter into a 3 year contract with an option to extend for a further 1 year with qualified providers, commencing on the 1st April 2017.

This service will be commissioned via an AQP process, therefore there will be no guaranteed volumes of activity for those providers that qualify to deliver the service. Payment is based on activity only as identified within the schedule of rates (please refer to the ITT documentation for details).  Patient choice will apply at point of referral to qualified providers.

Commissioners within NHS Coastal West Sussex CCG wish to commission a direct access non-obstetric ultrasound (NOUS) service.  This Service will deliver a safe, high quality service for NHS Coastal West Sussex CCG that offers patients a choice of provider, together with choice of location, date and time of appointments, excellent outcomes and an improved patient experience. 

The Commissioners will be holding a Provider Information Event for all interested parties on Monday 17th October 2016. To reserve up to three places per organisation, please email claire.ferguson5@nhs.net or call 01903 708617 with contact details of those who will be attending.

The provision of direct access non-obstetric ultrasound (NOUS) service is a contract for a period of 3 years commencing on the 1st April 2017 with option to extend for a maximum of a further two years. 

In 2013 the AQP direct access non-obstetric ultrasound (NOUS) was originally commissioned and seven providers were accredited, five remain. These providers will have their accreditation extended for a further period of three years and will continue to provide the service locally.   
It should be noted that under the Any Qualified Provider model, there will be no guarantees of volume or payment in the contracts awarded.

column47: Secure Delivery Services for the Home Office
column48:
Her Majesty's Passport Office (HMPO) is a directorate of the Home Office which provides passport services to British Nationals worldwide and, through the General Register Office (GRO), oversees the provision of civil registration services in England and Wales. HMPO supports Home Office priorities of cutting crime, reducing immigration, preventing terrorism and promoting growth.
 HMPO is looking for commercial partners to provide a range of Secure Delivery postal and courier services.
 It is necessary to collect centrally-printed passports and locally-printed passports and passport supporting documents from HMPO offices and to send these items to addresses in the UK and worldwide. The annual total is approximately 7 000 000 items of which 400 000 are for overseas delivery. There are also requirements to send a small volume of International passport applications from worldwide addresses to the UK, to send registration items from GRO and to provide an internal mail service for HMPO.
 HMPO wishes to broaden contract scope to include Home Office Secure Delivery requirements where possible. The current contract includes a UK Visas and Immigration requirement to collect centrally-printed biometric residence permits and send them to addresses in the UK and a National Crime Agency requirement for internal mail. The precise scope of requirements may change and will be advised in due course.
There are supporting requirements, for example, to reconcile items actually collected with those expected to be collected, to protect items, to track the location and status of items, to provide customer service, to action item-specific service requests and to provide operational and commercial support to delivery services.
 HMPO seeks innovative partners who can work flexibly to accommodate changes to requirements and procedures, to improve current deficiencies and begin to transform the service experienced by HMPO customers. The preference is to appoint a prime supplier who could potentially use subcontractors as required.
 No decision has been made on whether division into lots should occur. The Authority reserves the right to divide this requirement into lots.

Additional information: The Authority intends to conduct some Industry engagement with potential Suppliers which is currently planned for autumn 2015. The Authority will, if requested, facilitate the communication of an organisation's details to other prospective bidders who may not want to bid in their own right but may be interested in bidding to supply the services via either a joint venture or subcontract arrangement.

column47: THE PROVISION OF A MANAGEMENT INFORMATION SYSTEM & FINANCIAL ACCOUNTING SYSTEM FOR SCHOOLS & ACADEMIES
column48:
The Authority is seeking to implement a framework arrangement which will be divided into six Lots.

Lot One will be in respect of the Management Information System for all primary schools and academies nationally. 

Lot Two will be in respect of the Management Information System for all secondary schools and academies nationally.

Lot Three will be for a Financial Accounting System for Local Authority (LA) maintained primary schools nationally. 

Lot Four will be for a Financial Accounting System for Local Authority (LA) maintained secondary schools nationally.

Lot Five will be for a Financial Accounting System designed for use by primary Academies and Multi Academy Trusts available nationally. 

Lot Six will be for a Financial Accounting System for use by secondary Academies and Multi Academy Trusts nationally.

This Framework Agreement is intended to be available to all Local Authorities (LAs) throughout England and Wales. A list of all the relevant LAs may be found at: https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/491463/List_of_councils_in_England.pdf 

This Framework Agreement is also intended to be available to all schools throughout England and Wales. These schools include LA maintained, free schools, faith schools, Pupil Referral Units, Special Schools, Academies and Multi Academy Trusts. A list of all these schools may be found at: http://www.education.gov.uk/edubase/home.xhtml

column47: Tender for Datawarehouse Implementation Services
column48:
UCL has purchased IBM Datastage and IBM CDD to act broadly as the technology underpinning applications integration and data warehousing across the IT estate.

It operates a number of applications, including Oracle E-Business Suite for Financials and soon to be HR, SITS for Student Management, Research and Estates applications.

UCL would like to contract an organisation to partner with for the development of the central data-warehouse and potentially the implementation of an Operational Data Store (ODS) for the HR implementation project.

Data for the central data-warehouse will be transferred from and to multiple database types, including other data-warehouses and datamarts.  The transfers may require complex data transformations. They will capture data in both real-time and batch modes.

The success of this project will critically depend on a partner with exceptional data modelling skills and experience of developing data-warehouses, especially within the HE sector.  Based on their experience and skill, the bidder will be expected to develop data-models for the data-warehouses that meet current needs but also accommodate future needs where these can be reasonably foreseen or expected.  Thus the data models developed need to be durable and flexible.

The bidder will be required to develop appropriate documentation and configuration activities and deployment plans to help infrastructure architects and operational teams to understand the deliverable.  The documentation should enable those not familiar with the installation to i) reapply the solution in a new clean environment with the same configuration as that provided by the bidder and ii) development staff to understand the configuration and development that has been undertaken.

Additional information: OJEU Reference: 2016/S 170-306589

column47: The Provision of Proactive Primary Care and Pharmacy / Medicines Optimisation Support Service
column48:
North Manchester CCG wishes to commission a pilot proactive Primary Care and Pharmacy/Medicines Optimisation Support Service for care home residents within the North Manchester locality; the service will provide care home residents with the appropriate level of support that they require. There are 33 registered care homes in North CCG with a registered population capacity of up to 1,096 residents (figures correct as at June 2016)
 It is anticipated that this will be a joint project between a lead Provider and other provider organisations to support the care gap for residents within the NMCCG care homes population.
It is anticipated that the service will commence April 2017 involving the care homes registered within the new proposed Care Homes boundaries of neighbourhood three which has the largest care home capacity that equates to 8 homes.  The service will then be rolled out to include all registered Care Homes (with the exclusion of identified learning disabilities homes until decision after 12 months review) so that by March 2018, all remaining care homes are included and integrated within the four North Neighbourhoods receiving the proposed service provision as part of One Team Place Based Care. 
This procurement will be run as a bespoke, single stage procurement procedure. Bidders wishing to express an interest in participating in the Invitation to Tender (ITT) stage should register on https://nhssbs.eu-supply.com and look for tender reference number 25943.
The ITT documentation will be available from 8th December 2016 and should be completed and submitted by the closing date of 13th January 2017.

column47: RSSB1982 Supplier Assurance Management Services
column48:
The current Rail Industry Supplier Qualification Scheme (RISQS) was developed to assist buyers search for suppliers working or wishing to work within Great Britain's (GB) Rail Industry by providing a fair, open and transparent third party qualification process. RISQS helps to reduce the duplication of effort that organisations see from capability checks (e.g. Pre-Qualification Questionnaires (PQQs) and systems assessments) carried out by multiple buyers. It gives suppliers of all sizes an equal opportunity to demonstrate their capabilities and market their products and services whilst ensuring compliance to cross industry standards. RISQS services include collection of the industry's supplier pre-qualification questionnaire, verification of the data provided and audits for suppliers that have indicated they provide services that require audit. The electronic collection and verification of data Services are included in Lot 1 and the audit Services in Lot 2. Please see associated specifications for further details.

Additional information: Due to technical issues with Contracts Finder Appendix C is divided in 3 documents. We expect this to be rectified by close of play 09/12/16. Should you need to review this appendix before then please contract shareditt@rssb.co.uk.


Please submit your responses before the deadline given in this notice by emailing shareditt@rssb.co.uk.

column47: IT Training Services Framework
column48:
Lot 1 - IT Professionals
Within the Environment Agency we have approx. 200 ICT Professional staff in Corporate Information Services (CIS). We have IT professionals in three hubs - Bristol, Warrington and Bridgwater.  Within 2017/18 we are likely to merge with Defra ICT (DDTS - Defra Digital, Data and Technology Services).  
This Lot is to provide learning resources for ICT staff, initially for CIS.  We also expect other ICT teams within the Environment Agency to use this contract.  In time, our Defra colleagues (currently c260) may need to use this contract, in addition.  
The provider must be able to provide all learning resources for an ICT organisation, excluding those for the project profession (catered for through another contract).  Some of these learning resources will be commercial off the shelf accredited courses, delivered accredited training professionals, with a track record of successful delivery to the public sector. 

Lot 2 - IT Training for users (COTS and training in project deployments)
Within the Environment Agency we have approx. 10,000 staff. Approximately 9,000 use ICT.  Whereas we have operational staff who would not use IT at all apart from through their team leaders, many do.  These need the everyday skills in ICT - Microsoft Office 2013 at different levels and in bespoke systems, usually through projects (systems upgrades and deployments).  
Initially this contract is to support the ICT requirements of users in the Environment Agency but going forward this contract may be used to support ICT requirements in Defra.

This requirement will have a Supplier Selection Stage, which must be completed in order to qualify for the ITT stage.  Following the SSC stage, a maximum of 6 suppliers in each Lot will be issued an ITT.

Additional information: 
Information and formalities necessary for evaluating if the requirements are met:
Suppliers Instructions How to Express Interest in this Tender~: 1. Register your
company on the eSourcing portal (this is only required once) - Browse to the
eSourcing Portal: https://defra.bravosolution.co.uk and click the link to register -
Accept the terms and conditions and click 'continue' - Enter your correct business
and user details - Note the username you chose and click 'Save' when complete - You
will shortly receive an email with your unique password (please keep this secure) 2.
Express an Interest in the tender - Login to the portal with the username/password -
Click the 'PQQs / ITTs Open To All Suppliers' link. (These are Pre-Qualification
Questionnaires or Invitations to Tender open to any registered supplier) - Click on
the relevant PQQ/ ITT to access the content. - Click the 'Express Interest' button at
the top of the page. - This will move the PQQ /ITT into your 'My PQQs/ My ITTs' page.
(This is a secure area reserved for your projects only) -You can now access any
attachments by clicking 'Buyer Attachments' in the 'PQQ/ ITT Details' box 3.
Responding to the tender - Click 'My Response' under 'PQQ/ ITT Details', you can
choose to 'Create Response' or to 'Decline to Respond' (please give a reason if
declining) - You can now use the 'Messages' function to communicate with the buyer
and seek any clarification - Note the deadline for completion, then follow the
onscreen instructions to complete the PQQ/ ITT - There may be a mixture of online and
offline actions for you to perform (there is detailed online help available) You must
then submit your reply using the 'Submit Response' button at the top of the page. If
you require any further assistance please consult the online help, or contact the
eTendering help desk.

Our requirement was to procure consultancy support for the Devolution Programme Team and Policy Leads across NHS England to undertake detailed policy analysis and to develop a policy framework for devolution of NHS England functions. We were looking for a Consultant who could provide strategic and policy capacity and capability to: 
 undertake detailed policy analysis and development with NHS England leads to develop an NHS England policy position on the devolution of each of NHS England's relevant functions to local systems
 co-develop with NHS England colleagues a policy framework that supports the design and implementation of devolution of NHS England functions 
 set out the key questions and implications for both local systems and NHS England in terms of each overarching 'devolution' model
 co-develop with NHS England a set of clear recommendations and requirements for secondary legislation that will support the successful implementation and delivery of local government devolution of NHS England functions

column47: HCC Aug 16 - The Provision of Community Dementia Support Services - AWARD
column48:
This is an award notice and this tender opportunity is now closed.
      
      The County Council has commissioned a countywide Service which provides a range of support to people with dementia or memory problems, their carer and family. The Service is split into three lots: 
      
      Lot 1: Activity, Information and Infrastructure
      - Single point of access for Lot 1, 2 and 3, with basic advice and information
      - Work with communities, providers and other partners to make services accessible to people with dementia/ memory problems and build community resilience
      - Provide a range of mainly group based, local, community services
      
      Lot 2: Specialist Dementia Support
      - Time limited, 1:1 support offered to every person diagnosed with dementia (and their carer)
      - Ongoing source of 1:1 support/ advice/ navigation for any carer/ person with dementia/ MCI whose needs cannot be met by Lot 1
      - Proactively support carers/ people with dementia identified as 'high risk' 
      
      Lot 3: Community Dementia Specialist Nurses (Start date 1st April 2016)
      - Intensive, preventative mental health support for a small cohort of carers at, or close to, crisis 
      
      The Contract is for an initial term of 2 years, with the option to extend for a further period of up to 36 months. The total annual funding across all three lots is approximately 1,457,000:
      Lot 1 - 636,000
      Lot 2 - 653,000
      Lot 3 - 168,000
      
      TUPE applies to this Contract.
      
      The successful tenderers are - 
      Lot 1 - Age UK Hertfordshire
      Lot 2 - Alzheimer's Society
      Lot 3 - Carers in Hertfordshire
      
      Contract Notice Number - 2016/S 157-285553

column47: 1508/311/SW/CTI/16 Steel/Nickel Base (Air) Heat Treatment Facility
column48:
1508/311/SW/CTI/16 Steel/Nickel Base (Air) Heat Treatment Facility 

The University of Sheffield wishes to invite tenders for the supply of a Steel/Nickel Base (Air) Heat Treatment Facility for use within the Advanced Manufacturing Research Centre's Castings Group at Catcliffe, Rotherham.

Scope of Requirement:
The requirement is for a Steel (Air) Heat Treatment Facility which has the ability to heat treat steel/Nickel based castings up to 1250 degrees Celsius. 

It is envisaged that the facility will consist of two furnaces, a transfer system, quench tank, and all appropriate ancillary equipment for the complete heat treatment of castings.

This procurement is an open E.U. exercise carried out in support of a Prior Information Notice published on the 5th of August 2016 http://ted.europa.eu/udl?uri=TED:NOTICE:270822-2016:TEXT:EN:HTML

Completed tenders must be returned through the same e-tendering system.

column47: Concierge & Guarding Services
column48:
St Vincent's Housing Association (SVHA) is a charitable registered provider, founded in 1971 by the lay Catholic St Vincent's de Paul Society. It has circa 3,500 homes in 18 local authority areas with significant number of homes in Rochdale, Manchester, Bolton, Salford, Pendle, Ribble Valley and Hyndburn. 

SVHA sought bids from service providers to provide a concierge and guarding service for SVHA's three supported housing schemes in Manchester, Trafford and Blackburn. Services initially required under the contract are expected to include 168 hours per week guarding at the Blackburn foyer and Forrest Court, Flixton and 113 hours per week at the Manchester foyer. 

The outcome of the tender process was a single contract with one service provider. The contract will be an initial 2 years with 4 additional options to extend by a further 2 years (24 months), up to a maximum 10 years total contract term, subject to SVHA requirements and the performance of the successful service provider.  The contract will be available to SVHA and all subsidiaries both current and future. 

For the purpose of this notice, the contract duration and contract value is based on the maximum 10 years total contract term. The estimated total value is for information only, and no guarantees are given, nor are implied as to the value of business that will be placed with the successful service provider. 

Services initially required are in Manchester, Trafford and Blackburn but may also be used where SVHA has an operational requirement. SVHA reserves the right to add or remove sites or otherwise change the volume of work during the life of the contract up to a maximum increase in contract value of 200%. Additional sites will be priced on the same basis as the original sites for the services required.
